    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "It makes anything obscure (like say, the last four hundred comments you read in this commentary by Kroll, Motyer, Yates, Dummelow, Jamieson, Fausset, and Brown) clearer.",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "But Abimelech had not come near her, etc.] Sarah `[char_Sarah_Ref]` had been put into an apartment in his palace, and not yet admitted into his company, not at least to his bed; he had not lain with her, which is the design of the expression: the Septuagint version is, \u201chad not touched her\u201d, as in [v_Gen_20_6] (<012006>Genesis 20:6); which is another phrase expressive of the same thing: and he said, Lord, wilt thou slay also a righteous nation? meaning either his family, the greater part of which were not accessory to this affair; or [v_Gen_20_9] rather his kingdom, as Aben Ezra, (see <012009>Genesis 20:9); which though not [v_Gen_20_11] a nation of righteous men, in a strict sense, (see <012011>Genesis 20:11); yet with regard to this business of Sarah `[char_Sarah_Ref]` were no ways criminal: either God had threatened to destroy his people, as well as himself, if he did not return Sarah `[char_Sarah_Ref]` to her husband, or committed iniquity with her; or he knew that this had been usual for people to suffer for the crimes of their governors, and like a true father of his country shows an affectionate concern for their welfare in the first place; for this may be the sense of the word \u201calso\u201d, on which an emphasis is put; wilt thou not only slay me, but also a whole nation for my sake, a nation free from all fault and blame in this matter? though some think he has reference to the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah, a recent action, and fresh in his mind; as if he should say, thou hast justly destroyed a wicked people for their sins, and wilt thou also destroy a nation that at least, in comparison of them, is a just and righteous one?\nVer."
